bug.short_desc: The Chinese locales problem.

long_desc.thetext: The problem is related to the Chinese locales in general. If a doc is translated into Simplified Chinese only and not into Traditional Chinese, and if a Taiwanese user wants to display that doc, he/she expects to see the English doc but see the Simplified Chinese doc dispayed instead. This is incorrect as the English doc should be displayed by default if a Taiwanese translation cannot be found. One can simulate the problem by deleting some Taiwanese doc from the NLpack1 language pack which contains both doc translation into Simplified Chinese and Traditional Chinese.

Some more background: If a product chooses to support a locale (in this case traditional chinese, zh_TW) by translating the workbench content but not the doc, when you run said product under the zh_TW locale and then open a help book which doesn't have a TW translation (yes, this was done intentionally) then the doc for the zh (simplified) locale appears. I understand that this is how the runtime was designed to work. However, the product team in this case was hoping to get the English doc, as they likely got in pre-3.2 releases. The zh locales have changed since 3.1 when zh_CN and zh_TW were the only supported chinese locales (there were no NL files supplied for just "zh"). Now, the supported locales are zh (simplified), zh_TW (traditional), and zh_HK (Hong Kong). As you can see, having a less granular locale for simplified chinese causes the problem.
Is there anything we can do from a runtime perspective to solve this problem for 3.2.2 or 3.3?
I think bug 162000 and bug 162001 are duplicates of this bug ...
*** Bug 162000 has been marked as a duplicate of this bug. ***
*** Bug 162001 has been marked as a duplicate of this bug. ***

Correction: the change to the locales (to use zh instead of zh_CN) was made for 3.1, not after 3.1.
Note there is a help page that describes the mechanism Eclipse uses to locate nl files: org.eclipse.platform.doc.isv/guide/product_def_nl.htm

There are much more people using Simplified Chinese than Traditional Chinese worldwide. Therefore, Simplified Chinese is chosen as the default language for "zh" locale.
A portion of the Chinese characters are common to both Simplified Chinese and Traditional Chinese. When the Traditional Chinese translation for "zh_TW" locale is not found, it's better to show the Simplified Chinese translation, where the user may still be able to read a few characters and guessed the meanings, rather than not able to read anything thing at all. The behavior reported was working as designed. I'm resolving this bug as inavalid.

bug.short_desc: RECORD_UNKNOWN_FEATURE load option fails to function properly on certain types of root elements

long_desc.thetext:
In cases where the EPackage can be found for the root elements but the particular EClass cannot be found the resource still produces a ClassNotFoundException even though I pass this option.
To reproduce:
1) Use the EXTLibrary example from EMF 2) Add an extension parser for the "extlibrary" extension that points to a custom resource factory 3) Make this resource factory simply construct an XMIResourceImpl but adds the OPTION_RECORD_UNKNOWN_FEATURE->Boolean.TRUE entry to the default load options map of the resource. 4) Use the EXTLibrary creation wizard to create a new library file 5) Make the root of the resource one library with a single writer underneath it 6) Save the file 7) Close the editor 8) Open the file with a text editor and modify the "<extlib:Library" tag to be "<extlib:Librar" and modify the closing tag as well. (Simulating an EClass that has since been removed from the EPackage) 9) Open the file again with the EXTLibrary reflective editor
Result: ClassNotFoundException is thrown and the resource is not fully loaded
Expected Result: Because we are using the special record option, the resource should load normally but with an AnyType in the root of the resource.
I have tested changing only the xmi:type="extlib:Writer" to "extlib:Write" and the option works as designed. Also, I have tried changing only the library nsURI to make EMF unable to find the EPackage in the registry. Again, the load option works perfectly. This is the only case where it seems to fail.

Chris,
How about providing a JUnit, a standalone test case, patches for the library example, or simply a sample file, rather than a lengthy set of steps?
I'll reduce the severity until it's clear what exactly is being blocked in such a complete and total way that no workaround on your end is possible. After all, the scenario you've outlined is a garbage file containing nothing that even closely resembles a valid model, so what you could possibly do with this result if you could load it without throwing exceptions isn't clear at all.
As far as I'm concerned, options such recording unknown features are only as powerful as the test cases against which they have been tested. The meaning of this option has already been extended far beyond the original design intent. When we consider a new test case that tests a scenario that's never before been considered, we can *enhance* the current behavior to address that case, but arguments that there is a critical/blocking need to load a garbage file without exceptions is pretty thin. I.e., this is more of an enhancement to existing support than something critical and a complete show stopper in nature.
Easy to reproduce test cases will get you faster results than will driving the severity to the max; the later approach is most likly to just be annoying.

long_desc.thetext:
This bug covers several defects in the algorithm for computing the feature qualifier suffix. These defects are grouped together because it is extremely likely that they will all be fixed at the same time.
(1) Certain increases in the qualifier of a plugin can result in a decrease of the qualifier suffix for the feature. To trigger the bug, there has to be a slight increase in one digit of the plugin's qualifier and a large decrease in the subsequent digit.
For example, take a feature containing one plugin. The following plugin version numbers result in the following qualifier suffixes: 1.2.3.aaa-0z-aaa -> ------ooo-3B-ooo 1.2.3.aaa-10-aaa -> ------ooo-32-ooo The qualifier suffix decreased ('B' -> '2') even though the plugin version increased ('0' -> '1').
(2) The qualifier suffix can decrease from one build to the next if the longest qualifier among the plugins gets shorter, even if that qualifier increases in value.
For example, take a feature containing two plugins. The following plugin version number pairs result in the following qualifier suffixes: 4.5.6.xyz, 1.2.3.abccccc -> --------1022qqqq 4.5.6.xyz, 1.2.3.abcd -> -----------1022r The qualifier suffix decreased ('1' -> '-') even though the plugin version increased ('c' -> 'd').
(3) The qualifier suffix will remain unchanged if some '-' characters are appended to the qualifier of a plugin, where the plugin qualifier in question is not the longest qualifier of all the plugins in the feature.
For example, take a feature containing two plugins. The following plugin version number pairs result in the following qualifier suffixes: 1.2.3.abcdefg, 4.5.6.xyz -> --------1022rstu 1.2.3.abcdefg, 4.5.6.xyz-- -> --------1022rstu The qualifier suffix was unchanged even though the plugin version increased (blank -> '-').

1) This is caused by an incorrect value for "shift". '-' is being used. We really want to map the character back onto 0-63 (or 1-64, see comment for (3)), so the proper shift value will depend on which range (ie 0-9, a-z, A-Z) the character is in.
2) Do we maybe want the actual result to be: 1022qqqq-------- 1022r----------- In this case, the padding with '-' becomes unnecessary.
3) This is caused again by the shift value being '-', after shift, '-' goes to 0, and the result then is just whatever we got from the other plugin. So adding '-' does nothing if there is another plugin with a qualifer with length greater or equal. This implies maybe we actually want to shift the characters onto 1-64 instead of 0-63 for the sum.
See patch in bug 157049. It fixes all of the problems described here.

bug.short_desc: Feature qualifier suffix doesn't handle nested features correctly

long_desc.thetext:
The algorithm for calculating the feature qualifier suffix considers only part of the qualifier of the versions of included features. The algorithm looks only at the qualifier suffix of the included feature. It ignores the part of the qualifier that normally comes from the CVS tag for the feature.
This was done to limit the length of the qualifier suffix. The suffix for the outer feature would be unacceptably long if it took into account the entire qualifier of the nested feature. The qualifier suffix was chosen (rather than the first part of the qualifier) because it changes more frequently and is more likely to result in correct behavior of the outer feature's version number.
But there are cases where it can result in incorrect behavior, in the outer feature's version number decreasing when it should have increased. Assume that the feature org.eclipse.platform includes the feature org.eclipse.rcp. Assume also that at some point in time, a plugin is removed from org.eclipse.rcp, but no other changes are made anywhere. It is likely that the qualifier suffix for org.eclipse.rcp will decrease due to the plugin being removed, but that in itself is not a problem because the CVS tag for the feature will have changed, causing the qualifier as a whole (and therefore the feature version number) to increase. But when org.eclipse.platform is next built, it will look only at the qualifier suffix of org.eclipse.rcp, which decreased. As a result, the qualifier suffix for org.eclipse.platform will decrease. No other part of its version number will change (since its feature.xml was not changed at all), so its version number as a whole will decrease, which is bad.
There is no way for the qualifier suffix to always behave correctly while limiting its length to something that everyone would consider reasonable. Since the algorithm doesn't have access to any past builds (or future builds), it can't know how the parts of the included features' versions will change over time, so it can't know which characters could or could not be safely ignored.
So this bug is a plea to reconsider the trade off between qualifier suffix length and correctness. Is having a shorter suffix worth sometimes having incorrect version numbers? Could any changes be made to PDE Build (or could external tools be used) to at least detect these situations (so they could be worked around)?
See also bug 176010 for losing the last digit of the cvs tag in the feature qualifier.
This has been fixed in M6. Now we have other problems with the length of the generated suffixes.... oh well :-)
Apparently it has not been fixed. David could you please investigate and provide a patch since you have expertise in this area.

The only fix is to use the entire qualifier (both the context and the suffix parts) of the nested feature in the computation of the suffix for the outer feature. But that would cause the qualifier of the outer feature to become too long. As long as we need to limit the length of qualifiers, the current scheme of using just the suffix of nested features is probably the best we can do. It would take some fundamental changes to qualifier suffixes before we can fix this properly.
Resolving this as Won't Fix.

Ironically, I think this may be fixed by my idea to shorten the qualifier. That is, the a feature suffix would not include the suffix of nested features, only the qualifier portion. It would instead recursively get the qualifiers from the plugins in the nested feature. Whether or not this would actually shorten the suffix is an open question, but it may address this bug.

I thought about Andrew's idea of the outer feature using the versions of the nested feature's plugins when computing the outer suffix. But that doesn't completely solve the problem.
If the nested feature removes a couple plugins, the outer feature's version will likely decrease, even if the nested feature's version was updated. This is because there will be fewer things contributing to the outer feature's suffix, so the sum of the major version numbers (encoded at the beginning of the suffix) will decrease.

bug.short_desc: PrivilegedRunnable is causing corruption of transactions

long_desc.thetext:
Assume a thread X owning transaction T creates a privileged runnable, and executes it on threadY. startPrivilege creates a new transaction lock and pushes the original lock on a stack. If another thread Z requests for a transaction lock at this point, it waits on this new transaction lock. endPriviledge releases the transaction lock, and the waiting thread (Z) gets this lock. This is bad because the transaction was initially created by X and now Z owns this.
This is causing transaction corruption, and messages like transaction isn't owned by thread.

Even startPrivileged can result in hijacking of the transaction, because the newly created transaction lock is available for other threads to pick up.

bug.short_desc: BUTTON_2 events/ctrl-click in embedded SWT_AWT components received incorrectly

long_desc.thetext:
AWT/Swing components in an embedded SWT_AWT Frame do not received mouse events. Instead the events are received in the components' container.
If the attached code is run on Windows, the mouse events are received as expected in the JPanel. If is it run on Mac OS X, the mouse events are received in the Frame instead.
(attachment to follow)

Created an attachment (id=52575) simple application illustrating the bug
Run this code on Windows, click inside the panel, and see that the mouse events are received in the JPanel.
Run this code on Mac OS X, click inside the panel, and see that the mouse events are received in the Frame.
This belongs to me. It's a problem with event delivery in the embedding code.
Scott - I was just wondering if you see this bug on the horizon?

I don't see an easy fix for this one. It's a problem with managing focus and getting the AWT to recognize that the embedded frame is focused first, and then the panel. But, I am looking at it this week.

The problem here is that because there's no heavyweight AWT component, nothing delivers the events to the JPanel. As a workaround, if you use a java.awt.Panel instead of a javax.swing.JPanel (or put the JPanel inside the Panel) the code works as expected. This is not the first report of this that I've seen.

/** * Creates a new java.awt.Frame. This frame is the root for * the AWT components that will be embedded within the composite. In order * for the embedding to succeed, the composite must have been created * with the SWT.EMBEDDED style. *

* IMPORTANT: As of JDK1.5, the embedded frame does not receive mouse events. * When a lightweight component is added as a child of the embedded frame, * the cursor does not change. In order to work around both these problems, it is * strongly recommended that a heavyweight component such as java.awt.Panel * be added to the frame as the root of all components. *

* * @param parent the parent Composite of the new java.awt.Frame * @return a java.awt.Frame to be the parent of the embedded AWT components * * @exception IllegalArgumentException
    *
  • ERROR_NULL_ARGUMENT - if the parent is null
    • *
  • ERROR_INVALID_ARGUMENT - if the parent Composite does not have the SWT.EMBEDDED style
    • *
* * @since 3.0 */
Does this mean it's an accident, then, that it works on Windows?

Yes. There were all kinds of problems in this area depending on the platform and the JDK (if I remember correctly, even between the same version of the JDK on different platforms). We strongly recomend that application programmers put a panel as the first child of the SWT_AWT frame.
If this fixes the problem on the Mac, then I would close this bug.
Okay -- that's good enough for me. Putting an AWT Panel and then adding a JPanel on top of it works for me using the latest Java 5 update for 10.4, so I'm resolving this as WONTFIX.
Created an attachment (id=59107) simple application including workaround illustrating the right-click problem

Adding an AWT Panel as the first child of the embedded frame solves the problem for left-clicks, but not for right-clicks. Right-clicks are received in the parent (in this case, the AWT Panel) until the JPanel receives focus.
I've attached an application that demonstrates the problem:
A right-click on the JPanel (the large bordered area in the window) is received in the parent component (in this case, an AWT Panel.)
A left-click on the JPanel (the large bordered area in the window) is received in the JPanel. Subsequent right-clicks are also received in the JPanel.
If the application is restarted and the button labelled "Focus JPanel" is clicked, subsequent right-clicks will be received in the JPanel as expected.
Note that this may now be a duplicate of https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=162038.

A right-click on the Mac is the trigger for popup menus, so it may not be causing the Panel to receive focus. Luke, can you please file a bug at bugreport.apple.com with your test case? That way you'll know when we fix it in the JVM. I also renamed the bug to reflect the new problem.

bug.short_desc: Alternative approach to remote synchronization

long_desc.thetext:
There is some confusion about task categories and repository queries. Right now, when creating task/issue you don't know if it will appear in query or not, because query runs at the server side. as a work around, task is being added to the root of task list or into the Archive category. So, user does not have complete control on the structure of the task list and Archive category is getting severely cluttered.
I would like to suggest some changes in the architecture of the task list that would resolve these issues and will give more flexibility on task management and repositories integration.
The idea is to always create local tasks. Each task can be (optionally) linked to one (or more) repository. In this case, local changes will be promoted remotely, as well as remote changes will be brought back locally.
Then any category could also have one (or more) linked query that would bring in new issues created in remote repository. For these query hits user could create local tasks, either explicitly, or by scheduling, assigning or adding cc'ing self to the task. After that these tasks will be showing new updates. Note that user won't need query to see changes on monitored tasks.
This approach would allow nice mix of local and remote tasks within same category.
Couple more things:
-- Archive category should be created per category, so you could still scope searches per category even for archived/completed tasks
-- Described approach would eliminate case when the same task appear multiple times on Task List view in workweek mode (i.e. from queries like all project issues and all mine issues), which is quite annoying.
-- It would also allow to have same issue in multiple repositories (i.e. company private and public)

This trace shows that: - on a fast machine, we manage to construct two successive but structurally different instances of State for project P1 within the same millisecond; - we rely on no two states for the same project to have the same lastStructuralBuildTime unless they denote the same structural state. In other words, the millisecond precision is not enough on fast machine to identify projects states.
The test case is a bit contrived since the projects are very small indeed. But we could still expect small projects to happen (especially in the learn by doing phases).
Using a smaller precision (nanoseconds) is not an option with J2SE 1.4.
This leaves us with two options: - refine the use of State#buildNumber in case of full builds of projects that participate in a cycle; policy might be to increment the build number if a project is involved into a full build but has already undergone a build within the same millisecond; this might collide with other uses of buildNumber, hence should be examined carefully; - introduce a build ticker that, using the timer or not, would provide unique build numbers on a system-wide basis; would probably be a function best located at the base builders level (not Java builder).
In both cases, we would now have a reliable sequencing of project states, but the use of the full sequence identifier (say the combination of lastStructuralBuildTime and buildNumber if option 1 above is retained) would have to be leveraged throughout the code in general, and within State#wasStructurallyChanged in particular.

bug.short_desc: [type hierarchy] Generic - Show type hierarchy

long_desc.thetext:
"Show type hierarchy" shows all the classes that extends a certain type but ignores the type generic.
e.g.
Map<String, String> m;
If I'll hit the F4 button on the Map<String, String> I'll get all the classes that implements Map (which can be a huge number) e.g. HashMap (which doesn't implements Map<String, String>) and not all the classes that implements Map<String, String>.

Type hierarchies currently only show the declaration hierarchy, but not concrete parameterized types.
We could think about adding a new mode to consider resolved types. However, this would not give a much smaller hierarchy, since many generic subtypes of Map<K,V> would still be part of the hierarchy (e.g. Hashtable<String, String>) while only a few (like Properties, which extends Hashtable<Object,Object>) could be left out.
As soon as wildcards come into play, the hierarchy explodes. E.g. Map<String, ? extends Object>, Map<String, ? extends Serializable>, and Map<String, ? super String> are just a few of the many supertypes of Map<String, String>. The subtypes of Collection<? extends Object> are not even a finite set.
In summary: The resolved type hierarchy could not be shown completely, and showing only parts of it would IMO be confusing.

bug.short_desc: "Organize imports" includes unecessary classes

long_desc.thetext:
Reproduction sequence:
- In a source file, have some javadoc that refers to another class 'foo' present in your project, but actually not "used" in the class. - Trigger "organize import" feature. - Eclipse imports 'foo' in the class, although it is not necessary. The import statement can be deleted manually without causing compilation error.
Could be reproduced with Version: 3.2.0 Build id: M20060629-1905
And on 2 other versions (colleagues... including 3.2.1), although in 1 case, the bug did not show (3.2.1 too).
It may cause problems when the references class is available to the Eclipse project while it is not to the build server (for instance, a test class that's not included during deployment).

Actually, that's a requirement from JavaDoc. It needs to know (when you have @see Foo) what the fully qualified name of the class is, and it uses the imports for that.
I think if you used the full package (@see org.example.Foo) then you wouldn't get the import.
Organize import does import classes needed in javadoc if the javadoc comment processing is enabled. Closing as INVALID.

"I think if you used the full package (@see org.example.Foo) then you wouldn't get the import."
Yes, indeed.

I was originally to file this under PDE/UI, but in fact, the underlying processing of the launcher arguments still doesn't allow anybody to use arguments in launcher configurations that have spaces. See the ticket where I originally entered a discussion on, ticket #88766:
-
Alex, the eclipse.ini file cannot possibly come out ok if your usage is the following: "My product is called 'My Application' and I want to use the -name feature of the eclipse launcher to set that"
In the product editor, since no documentation says otherwise, naively you would enter in the launcher argument multi-line text:
-name My Application
This however causes the ini to have three lines. Next step, you think "I guess I should have quoted the app name so they dont cut it up":
-name "My Application"
which, since the quotes aren't processed, just gets you:
-name "My Application"
in the ini file (which then gives a command line of "-name" ""My" "Application"")
Finally, if you try Alex's last example, say:
> <launcherArgs> > <programArgs>-name >hello there world</programArgs> > </launcherArgs> > >where "-name" and "hello there world" were put on 2 separate lines in the >product editor.
As alex points out, that still doesn't work:
>However, when exporting, the eclipse.ini looks like: >-name >hello >there >world
instead of -name hello there world
At least, that's my understanding of Eddie's situation.
In Summary:
The *BUG* is very simple: there is NO WAY to use a space in ANY ARGUMENT in ANY LAUNCHER built via PDE.
I see the culprit: the use of StringTokenizer to process the launcher arguments, without offering any space-escape syntax.
A part of the problem is in PDE Build but another part may be in PDE UI, cc'ing Wassim to get his opinion.

I am not sure how the *.ini file gets processed, but we were giving the instructions to put each word on a separate line.
Perhaps there was ambiguity in the request, and the intent was to put each argument on a separate line.

> If that is the case, we should stop using StringTokenizer and use > ExecutionArguments from Debug to do the parsing of tokens.

- Added optional systemTypeIds attribute to extension point subsystemConfigurations - SubSystemConfigurationProxy implementation updated to evaluate system type names _and_ system type id on initialization - Wildcards * and ? possible for system type names and system type ids - If neither system type names nor ids are specified, the configuration defaults to support all system types - JUnit test added - subsystemConfigurations extension point documentation updated

My only concern is that I'm not so sure it's a good idea to add a new extension point slot for "systemTypeIds" as optional.
In my opinion, the current functionality of registering against systemTypeNames is simply a bug and should be removed as soon as possible (for instance, because it makes systemTypeNames not translatable in other languages).
So what I'd expect is at least to make the current systemTypes slot deprecated; or go one step further and leave the current slot in place but give it a new interpretation as registering against IDs instead of Names (which most people had expected anyways).
We are changing so many things with RSE 2.0, and we have so few existing "customers", that I don't see a need to keep buggy functionality around for compatibility. People have to change the names into ids.
Comments?

Ok. - Attribute "systemTypes" of extension point subsystemConfigurations marked deprecated - Replaced RSE own use by attribute "systemTypeIds"
If it will be removed completelly is a "management" decision. Please discuss in next committers meeting. - must be documented in release notes - May not be obvious to adaptors as it depends on the Eclipse PDE error/warnings level if invalid extension point usage is annotated.

I think it would be better to simply change the implementation to interpret the systemTypes parameter as IDs instead of names, rather than deprecating it. This would force a change and as Martin noted, we don't have too many RSE customers at this point so the hit would really be to "known" customers.

One problem with this is that there is zero cut-over time. From one moment to the other, somebody who correctly had a systemType Name in his plugin, needs an id. And it cannot be detected at development time (only strings!) but only fails at runtime. So the user, who's not reading release notes of course, wonders what's wrong!
Another issue (don't know!) might be that existing workspaces from RSE 1.x fail to load under 2.0 which would also be a problem if the workspace can't be recovered.
It's not that I'm totally against the step proposed by Kushal, I just want to outline the potential issues.

- The attribute "systemType" could be easely removed. - I would really prefer to specify the system type ids via the new attribute "systemTypeIds". a) As the removal of systemType attribute is going to break old contributions, it doesn't matter if the attribute is renamed as well. b) The name "systemTypeIds" of the attribute is much much clearer than only "systemTypes" c) Changing only the interpretation of the content of "systemTypes" as this will make it almost unbearable hard to find out why contributions may not work anymore (even if clearly communicated, people tends to oversee the announcements).

Build time error is much better than runtime error.

bug.short_desc: Open and close events are not sent.

long_desc.thetext: PC open and close events are not sent in workgroup. As a result it also isn't possible to say who is online or offline. This is one of the basic events.

One problem was that each project container need to have team repository defined. It it is not defined, then the open/close events are not sent. After adding the team repository the open / close event is sent, but only to the person who has opened or closed the container, but not to the rest of the team.

The events weren't sent to server, but were just distributed locally and not propagated. I sometimes experienced that first open event wasn't sent but it would require a more investigation.
I think there should be an other interface to send events to work group and locally. Now, the event is sent to OSGi Event and the ECF sends it if there is remote.uri parameter set. Additionally now there is a fixed remote address ecftcp://localhost:4700/ . It must be parametrized.
It think the best possible solution would be creation of a special repository type that would represent an event distribution service. Then you would obtain a repository adapter for this and post an event through it. It would provide both flexibility of eventing mechanism and would distinguish local from network message broadcast.
But there is a problem that it should also listen for remote events. So the the adapter would have to be opened as soon as the PC is opened. This could be done by the event handling done by extension points that I was saying at dev mailing list.
